---
description: "Code conventions for Excalidraw components and utilities"
globs: packages/**/*.ts,packages/**/*.tsx
alwaysApply: false
---

# Code Conventions

## Components

- Functional components + hooks preferred (App.tsx is the notable class component exception)
- Props: `interface` when extending HTML/React types, `type` for simple prop objects
- Named exports preferred; default exports used for main/complex components (e.g., App, LayerUI, ConfirmDialog)
- Colocated styles: `ComponentName.scss` alongside component file

## TypeScript

- Strict mode enabled — minimize `any`, avoid `@ts-ignore`
- Use `import type { X } from "..."` for type-only imports
- Path aliases for cross-package imports: `@excalidraw/common`, `@excalidraw/element`, `@excalidraw/utils`
- Relative imports for within-package references

## File Naming

- PascalCase for components: `Avatar.tsx`, `LayerUI.tsx`, `Sidebar.tsx`
- camelCase/kebab-case for utilities: `appState.ts`, `editor-jotai.ts`, `animated-trail.ts`
- PascalCase for component folders: `ColorPicker/`, `Sidebar/`, `CommandPalette/`
- kebab-case for utility/feature folders: `live-collaboration/`, `welcome-screen/`, `drop-down-menu/`

## Tests

- Colocated with source for components: `Sidebar/Sidebar.test.tsx`
- Separate `tests/` folder for utility packages: `packages/element/tests/`
- Naming: `{FileName}.test.ts(x)`
- Framework: Vitest with jsdom environment

## Exports & Imports

- Barrel exports via `index.ts` in each package (`export * from "./module"`)
- Re-export types with `export type { ... }`
- Cross-package: use `@excalidraw/*` aliases, not relative paths

## How to verify

- `yarn test:typecheck` — confirms strict mode compliance, no type errors
- `yarn test:code` — ESLint enforces import ordering, `import type` usage, and restricted imports
- `yarn test:other` — Prettier validates formatting
- `grep -rn "export default" packages/excalidraw/components/ | head -20` — check default exports are only on main components
- `grep -rn "from '\.\./\.\./\.\./packages/" packages/` — must return nothing (no relative cross-package imports)